WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.661
MetaObjects generates your code.

2
00:00:02.661 --> 00:00:04.215
But it doesn't have to.

3
00:00:04.215 --> 00:00:10.158
The same model can drive your app live, at runtime — and that's a different way to ship.

4
00:00:10.158 --> 00:00:11.847
This is runtime metadata.

5
00:00:13.247 --> 00:00:19.505
One generic function built this grid — the columns, the headers, the cell types — straight from the live model.

6
00:00:19.505 --> 00:00:20.576
No code generation.

7
00:00:20.576 --> 00:00:24.071
And the same function does it for any object you've described.

8
00:00:24.071 --> 00:00:24.973
Let me show you.

9
00:00:26.373 --> 00:00:28.535
There are two ways to use one model.

10
00:00:28.535 --> 00:00:32.499
Generate code from it — a snapshot, perfect until something moves.

11
00:00:32.499 --> 00:00:36.882
Or load the model at runtime and drive behavior directly — the live feed.

12
00:00:36.882 --> 00:00:38.083
Most teams use both.

13
00:00:39.483 --> 00:00:41.095
So here's the model itself.

14
00:00:41.095 --> 00:00:47.782
Look closely — the validators live right on the fields, and the grid layout sits beside them, all just metadata.

15
00:00:47.782 --> 00:00:53.693
This one file is what the runtime reads; everything you're about to see is driven straight from it.

16
00:00:55.093 --> 00:00:56.327
Here's the live one.

17
00:00:56.327 --> 00:01:01.574
Build grid walks your loaded model — fields, views, types — and returns your columns.

18
00:01:01.574 --> 00:01:04.968
Notice what's not here: no object name, no field names.

19
00:01:04.968 --> 00:01:09.597
The same call works for Task, for Project, and for anything else you model.

20
00:01:10.997 --> 00:01:14.030
That's the whole thing — a few generic lines.

21
00:01:14.030 --> 00:01:18.275
The rows carry their own model, so it asks each one what it is.

22
00:01:18.275 --> 00:01:23.127
Task, Project, Invoice — one function renders them all, with no codegen.

23
00:01:24.527 --> 00:01:25.978
And it's not just grids.

24
00:01:25.978 --> 00:01:28.397
Validation runs from the live model too.

25
00:01:28.397 --> 00:01:34.866
No generated validator — the required and length rules come straight from the metadata, checked at runtime.

26
00:01:36.266 --> 00:01:48.156
Load the model, and it drives a whole lot: dynamic CRUD, validation, relationships, server-driven grids and forms, prompt rendering and tolerant extraction — none of it regenerated.

27
00:01:49.556 --> 00:01:52.799
So when do you generate, and when do you drive it live?

28
00:01:52.799 --> 00:01:56.927
Generate for build-time artifacts — typed, committed, dependency-free.

29
00:01:56.927 --> 00:02:05.183
Drive it live when codegen can't reach: a shipped app you can't redeploy, an agent that connects tomorrow, behavior that changes on the fly.

30
00:02:05.183 --> 00:02:07.896
A snapshot can't reach them; a live model can.

31
00:02:09.296 --> 00:02:10.353
That's the idea.

32
00:02:10.353 --> 00:02:15.045
Codegen is a snapshot of your model; runtime metadata is the live feed.

33
00:02:15.045 --> 00:02:19.077
Same model — generate the code, or drive it live, often both.

34
00:02:19.077 --> 00:02:21.655
Change the model, and behavior follows.

35
00:02:21.655 --> 00:02:24.496
Nothing to regenerate, nothing to redeploy.

36
00:02:25.896 --> 00:02:27.998
Drive your app from the model.

37
00:02:27.998 --> 00:02:30.660
Build grid ships in runtime-web today.

38
00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:35.494
This is part of the MetaObjects series — more at metaobjects dot dev.

39
00:02:35.494 --> 00:02:36.895
Thanks for watching.

